We recommended, and the MA agreed that:
For consistency on the estimated useful life and residual value of PPE, to revisit Annex A of COA Circular No. 2003-007, COA Circular 2015-002 and DPWH DO No. 176 s. 2015, and revise/update the lapsing schedule;
After revising/updating the lapsing schedule of PPE by including all vital and correct asset information, explicitly show the accurate computations of Depreciation Expenses, Accumulated Depreciation, and net book values of each item of PPE;
Effect the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts for the misstatements of depreciation expenses and the corresponding accumulated depreciation based on the revised/updated lapsing schedule; and
Update the PPELCs based on the revised lapsing schedule ensure that the total balance of PPELCs tally with the balances of controlling PPE accounts in the GL.

We recommended, and Management agreed to the following:
The IC to conduct the physical count of all inventory accounts and ensure that all goods received and on hand as of the end of the year are reported in the RPCI;
The MGSO to promptly prepare the monthly S/RSMI duly supported by approved Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and other supporting documents such as list of recipients of drugs and medicines, and timely submit the same to the MAO so that issuances thereof are timely recorded and accounted for in the books of accounts;
The MAO to coordinate with the MGSO for the submission of the S/RSMI, along with all necessary supporting documents, and draw a JEV to adjust the Drugs and Medicines and Accountable Forms, Plates and Stickers inventory accounts, as well as the related expense accounts, if not yet distributed; and
The MAO and the MGSO agreed to conduct regular reconciliation of their records to ensure that inventories and issuances recorded in the books are reconciled with the actual inventories on hand and held by the Municipality as of December 31, 2024.

We recommended, and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Institute collection efforts by sending collections letter/demand letter to loan borrowers based on the subsidiary schedule at hand;
Avail the remedies of COA Circular 2023-008 to clean and/or analyze the dormant Loans Receivable-Other accounts amounting P 151,151.12 and request for write-off thru the Municipal Mayor following the procedure outlined under Section 7 and 8 thereof.

The management thru the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Office to:
a. Procure and maintain availability of all the basic equipment for disaster preparedness as specified in the Minimum Standards for Disaster Preparedness, especially on the items identified;
b. Include in the LDRRM Investment Plan, the establishment of toilets for PWDs as well as an appropriate storage area in their designated evacuation center, and ensure its implementation;
c. Install Rainwater Collection System as alternative sources of water supply for the evacuation center; and
d. Evaluate and monitor the existing equipment and facilities for disaster preparedness to ensure compliance with the minimum standards and to further improve the LGUs capabilities to be disaster resilient.

The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Mayor to call the attention of the contractors of the three (3) projects that remained not completed to facilitate completion thereof as soon as possible;
For the 17 projects that are physically completed, to prepare the necessary reports as soon as possible and submit to the funding agency and request for inspection to this Office, together with its supporting documents to avoid delay in project inspection and evaluation by the Audit Team and COA-RTS; and
The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant to monitor the contractors’ compliance with the contract period/ duration and take appropriate legal action against the contractor for delayed completion of the project including imposition of Liquidated Damages.

The LGU GAD Focal Point System:
1. Adhere to the structure provided in the Joint Memorandum Circular and provide Technical Working Group to perform their roles and responsibilities;
2. Establish the LGU GAD Database to be used in identifying gender gaps/issues;
3. Provide GAD activity that is responsive to the identified GAD issue and attribute only projects and programs identified to address gender gaps.

